[{"id":30009,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In Kjeldahl method,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Per</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cent</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Where, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NV</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>= gram equivalent of ammonia</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>= weight of the organic compound&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><mi>excess</mi></munder><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math><br /><br />Total of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> used <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>6 mm&#160;=&#160;6&#160;x&#160;2&#160;=12&#160;gm&#160;equivalent</mtext></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> for back titration <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mn>0</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>2&#160;gm&#160;equivalent</mtext></math><br /><br />gm equivalent of&nbsp;remaining <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo></math>used for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;neutralisation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>equivalent</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>NV</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>equivalent</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Per&#160;cent&#160;of N</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>x</mi><mn>10</mn></mrow><mtext>1.4</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>10%</mtext></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29819,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>A chiral center (Asymmetric&nbsp;center) of an atom is the atom in a molecule that is bonded to four different chemical species. The chemical species is an atom/molecule with a specific molecular structure. In the following molecule, chiral carbon are marked with &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>*</mo></math>&#39;.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6dc3ab38-9b1c-4c31-b8ea-8fabdb012252-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 224px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30054,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["n-hexane","2, 3-dimethylbutane","2,2-dimethylbutane","2-methylpentane"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Cm6Q5YGRMcUSX_Wuq_qrn8AfbWwjnUUqjrMkHoxYJuc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":29644,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$273$","$27$","$2730$","$227$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Mass of carbon in the compound is calculated from the mass of $CO_2$ produced:<br><br>Mass of C $= \\dfrac{12}{44} \\times \\text{mass of } CO_2 = \\dfrac{12}{44} \\times 0.25 = \\dfrac{3}{44}$ g<br><br>Given that the percentage of carbon in the compound is $25\\%$:<br><br>$\\% \\text{ of C} = \\dfrac{\\text{Mass of C}}{\\text{Total mass } X} \\times 100$<br><br>$25 = \\dfrac{\\dfrac{3}{44}}{X} \\times 100$<br><br>$X = \\dfrac{3}{44} \\times \\dfrac{100}{25} = \\dfrac{3}{44} \\times 4 = \\dfrac{3}{11}$ g<br><br>$X \\approx 0.2727$ g<br><br>Verifying this using the percentage of hydrogen:<br><br>Mass of H $= \\dfrac{2}{18} \\times \\text{mass of } H_2O = \\dfrac{2}{18} \\times 0.12 = \\dfrac{1}{75}$ g<br><br>$\\% \\text{ of H} = \\dfrac{\\dfrac{1}{75}}{X} \\times 100 = 4.89$<br><br>$X = \\dfrac{100}{75 \\times 4.89} \\approx 0.2727$ g<br><br>Thus, $X = 272.7 \\times 10^{-3}$ g.<br><br>Rounding to the nearest integer, the required value is $273$.<br><br>Answer: $273$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29701,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"Lassaigne's test is a general test for detection of halogen, nitrogen and sulphur in an organic compound. These elements covalently bonded to the organic compounds, In order to detect them, these have to converted into ionic forms.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6_A2ZN24AvOcPt7m2-PiyDw1pBZpVxKpNHDhbbyU0Rw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30053,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(a), (b), (c), (d)","(d), (c), (b), (a)","(b), (c), (a), (d)","(c), (b), (a), (d)"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":29988,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylhex<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>diethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylbut<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ethylhex<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylhex<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c94b7cd-b48e-4eed-b5fd-3f3e4ded50cc-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 149px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Ethyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylhex<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30034,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Lactic acid","2- Butene","Phenol","None of these"],"answer":2,"solution":"phenol can exhibit tautomerism","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":30059,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["acetamide","thiourea","urea","benzamide"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29794,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The decrease in electron density of the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> bond of o,p-dinitrophenol, the polarity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> bond decreases. The electron withdrawing group <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>), withdraws electrons and disperses the negative charge. Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> group stabilizes the phenoxide ion. Hence, o,p-dinitrophenol is more acidic than p-nitrophenol and phenol.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OMe</mi></math> is an electron donating group, hence it increases electron density, there why making it less acidic.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Bu</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math> is an aliphatic alcohol. In phenoxide ion the negative charge is delocalized within the ring structure which makes it more stable than the aliphatic alcohols. In aliphatic alcohols there is no such delocalization stabilization. Therefore, phenols are more acidic and the resulting phenoxide ion is stabilized because of resonance.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02c71878-9222-453d-aed9-a9312d85f3f3.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 218px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29935,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"if molar mass of compound is M<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>/</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>88</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>/</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>188</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></math><br />so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>160</mn></math> gram/mole<br />Now&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;of bromine <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>160</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29677,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Partial pressure of $\\mathrm{N}_2=(900-15)=885 \\mathrm{~mm} \\mathrm{Hg}$<br />Mole of $\\mathrm{N}_2=\\frac{\\left(\\frac{885}{760} \\times 0.15\\right)}{(0.0821 \\times 300)}=0.0071$ <br />Moles $\\%$ of nitrogen in organic compound<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& =\\frac{(0.0071 \\times 28)}{1} \\times 10 \\\\<br>& =19.85 \\%<br />\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29809,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C, A, D, B","C, A, B, D&nbsp;","A, C, D, B","A, C, B, D"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The stability of a carbocation increases with the number of alkyl groups attached to the carbon atom, due to the inductive and hyperconjugation effects of the alkyl groups. The more the number of alkyl groups, the greater is the electron density on the positively charged carbon, and hence the more stable is the carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15fcb8ee-2e3d-4869-b617-f1da716fe54c.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 104px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>The above carbocation can be stabilised by resonance and hyperconjugation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7878c7e7-d4f9-4ea6-b738-d566fcb47f73.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 102px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation stabilised by resonance caused by three benzene rings. This carbocation is more stable than the previous carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b7c796bc-90a4-44df-82e3-dfba0897a3cb.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 110px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation stabilised by hyperconjugation. It is the least stable carbocation among the four carbocations given.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f08e1a51-1ec1-49a4-bfbb-17b2223fdac1.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 131px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation is the most stable carbocation among the four due to the resonance caused by bent orbitals.</p><p>From the given options Stability of carbocation:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p>The least stable carbocation will have the highest hydride affinity, because it is the most electron deficient and has the highest positive charge density. As a result, it will have the strongest attraction for a negatively charged hydride ion.</p><p>Hydride affinity order:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29910,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only in Resonance</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b77891c-b696-45fd-a48c-4367779ddc4e-image.png\" style=\"width: 311px; height: 422px;\" /></p><p>In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;positive charge is not in conjugation therefore resonance is not possible in these.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29724,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Bc75dTUyUiP7dmQCsfHJoGavaSafn_NK-AgvWxkFsFE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29680,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$15.71 \\%$","$20.95 \\%$","$17.46 \\%$","$7.85 \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\text { Pressure of } \\begin{aligned}<br />\\mathrm{N}_2 \\text { gas evolved } & =715-15 \\\\<br>& =700 \\mathrm{~mm} \\mathrm{Hg} \\\\<br>& =\\frac{700}{760} \\mathrm{~atm}.<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />\\therefore \\text { Mole of } \\mathrm{N}_2 \\text { evolved } & =\\frac{\\mathrm{PV}}{\\mathrm{RT}} \\\\<br>& =\\frac{700 \\times 60 \\times 10^{-3}}{760 \\times 0.0821 \\times 300} \\\\<br>& =0.0022 \\mathrm{~mole}<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />$\\therefore \\mathrm{wt}. \